{"parse":{"title":"Conservation of resources theory","pageid":55248218,"revid":856110506,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Conservation of Resources (COR) Theory</b>  is a <a href=\"/wiki/Psychological_stress\" title=\"Psychological stress\">stress</a> theory that describes the motivation that drives humans to both maintain their current resources and to pursue new resources. <sup id=\"cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> This theory was proposed by Dr. Stevan E. Hobfoll in 1989 as a way to expand on the literature of stress as a <a href=\"/wiki/Construct_(philosophy_of_science)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Construct (philosophy of science)\">construct</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  \n</p><p>Hobfoll posited that <a href=\"/wiki/Psychological_stress\" title=\"Psychological stress\">psychological stress</a> occurred in three instances; when there was a threat of a loss of resources, an actual net loss of resources, and a lack of gained resources following the spending of resources. From this perspective, resources are defined as things that one values, specifically objects, states, and conditions. <sup id=\"cite_ref-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  <b>COR</b> states that loss of these types of resources will drive individuals into certain levels of stress. <sup id=\"cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History_of_stress_theory\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History of stress theory</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Basic_principles_of_COR\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Basic principles of COR</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Areas_of_research\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Areas of research</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History_of_stress_theory\">History of stress theory</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Conservation_of_resources_theory&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History of stress theory\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><b>COR</b> was developed from various theories on the cause of stress.  <b>COR</b> development branches back to <a href=\"/wiki/Walter_Bradford_Cannon\" title=\"Walter Bradford Cannon\">Walter Bradford Cannon</a> (1932) who was one of the first researchers to study the concept of stress as it applies to humans, specifically in how stress can be withstood. <sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>  <a href=\"/wiki/Hans_Selye\" title=\"Hans Selye\">Hans Selye</a> (1950) took on Cannon\u2019s research on stress as a response and indicated that stress itself was designed as a way to protect the body from environmental challenges. <sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  \n</p><p>Other researchers such as Elliot and Eisdorfer (1982) defined stress as specifically being the stimulus and not the response, which had been accepted by some of the scientific community.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>  However, this theory is largely based on the homeostatic model of stress developed by Joseph McGrath (1970). <sup id=\"cite_ref-autogenerated1970_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-autogenerated1970-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>  It is in this theory that stress is defined as an imbalance between the environmental demand and the response capability of an organism. <sup id=\"cite_ref-autogenerated1970_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-autogenerated1970-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Basic_principles_of_COR\">Basic principles of COR</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Conservation_of_resources_theory&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Basic principles of COR\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>COR covers two basic principles involving the protection of resources from being lost. <sup id=\"cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  The first principle is called the <b>Primacy of Resource Loss.</b><sup id=\"cite_ref-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  This principles states that it is more harmful for individuals to lose resources compared to when there is a gain of resources.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  What this means, is that a loss of pay will be more harmful than the same gain in pay would have been helpful.    \n</p><p>The second principle is known as <b>Resource Investment.</b> <sup id=\"cite_ref-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;_2-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> This principle of <b>COR</b> states that people will tend to invest resources in order to protect against resource loss, to recover from losses, and to gain resources.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;_2-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Within the context of coping, people will invest resources to prevent future resource losses.  \n</p><p>From these two principles, <b>COR</b> has suggested a number of corollaries that can be applied to resource changes. <sup id=\"cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  They are as follows:\n</p>\n<ol><li>Individuals with higher resources will be set up for gains in resources.  Similarly, individuals with fewer resources are more likely to experience resource losses. <sup id=\"cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>Initial resource loss will lead to resource loss in the future.  <sup id=\"cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>Initial resource gains will lead to resource gains in the future.  <sup id=\"cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>A lack of resources will invariable lead to defensive attempts to conserve the remaining resources.  <sup id=\"cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></li></ol>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Areas_of_research\">Areas of research</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Conservation_of_resources_theory&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Areas of research\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><b>COR</b> has been utilized when studying work/family stress,<sup id=\"cite_ref-The_Conservation_of_Resources_Model_applied_to_work-family_conflict_and_strain_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-The_Conservation_of_Resources_Model_applied_to_work-family_conflict_and_strain-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-A_conservation_of_resources_view_of_the_relationship_between_work_engagement_and_work_interference_with_family_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-A_conservation_of_resources_view_of_the_relationship_between_work_engagement_and_work_interference_with_family-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>  <a href=\"/wiki/Occupational_burnout\" title=\"Occupational burnout\">burnout</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sources_of_social_support_and_burnout_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sources_of_social_support_and_burnout-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> and general stress.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>  In work/family stress, <b>COR</b> research has looked at how the distribution of one\u2019s resources have affected their home life, with some articles finding that putting too much of one\u2019s resources into one\u2019s work may lead to family problems at home.<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>  Research into <b>COR</b> and burnout has examined how the use of resources has impacted one\u2019s mood, with recent research finding that emotional exhaustion had the strongest relationship with depressive symptoms.<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>  \n</p><p>In regards to general stress, research has explored how the loss of resources impacts the levels of one\u2019s stress.<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>  It should be noted that COR has primarily been studied within the burnout and job fields, as the following meta-analyses will demonstrate.  There is currently no meta-analyses on COR within other areas of stress research.  \n</p><p>Multiple meta-analyses have been conducted with COR, specifically related to burnout. One meta-analyses by Lee and Ashforth (1996) examined the relationship between demand and resource correlates, behavioral and attitudinal correlate, and 3 different dimensions of job burnout. <sup id=\"cite_ref-autogenerated123_14-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-autogenerated123-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup>  It used COR as the basis for this research and found that the primacy of resource loss principle is supported.  It found that, over 58 sources, individuals tend to be sensitive to increased demands rather than resources received.  <sup id=\"cite_ref-autogenerated123_14-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-autogenerated123-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup>   \n</p><p>Job control and COR have been studied through a meta-analyses conducted by Park, Baiden, Jacob, &amp; Wagner (2009). <sup id=\"cite_ref-autogenerated2_15-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-autogenerated2-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>  This study tested COR using all constructs involved in job control and burnout which included constructs of autonomy, authority, skill discretion, and decision latitude. <sup id=\"cite_ref-autogenerated2_15-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-autogenerated2-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> Results indicate that the construct of job control, or the ability that one has to choose their actions from multiple options at their job, is related to depersonalization and personal accomplishment.  This study stated that COR is related to burnout in this way, but further studies should be conducted that use non-human service occupations.  <sup id=\"cite_ref-autogenerated2_15-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-autogenerated2-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Conservation_of_resources_theory&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-5\"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-6\"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-7\"><sup><i><b>h</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-8\"><sup><i><b>i</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Conservation_of_Resources._A_new_attempt_at_conceptualizing_stress_1-9\"><sup><i><b>j</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Hobfoll, Stevan (1989). \"Conservation of Resources. A New attempt at conceptualizing stress\". <i>The American Psychologist</i>. <b>44</b> (3): 513\u2013524.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+American+Psychologist&amp;rft.atitle=Conservation+of+Resources.+A+New+attempt+at+conceptualizing+stress&amp;rft.volume=44&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=513-524&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.aulast=Hobfoll&amp;rft.aufirst=Stevan&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AConservation+of+resources+theory\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;_2-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Getting_to_the_&quot;COR&quot;_2-5\"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Halbesleben, J.B.; Paustian-Underdal, S.C.; Westman, M (2014). \"Getting to the \"COR\": Understanding the Role of Resources in Conservation of Resources Theory\". <i>Journal of Management</i>. <b>40</b> (5): 1334\u20131364. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1177/0149206314527130\">10.1177/0149206314527130</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Management&amp;rft.atitle=Getting+to+the+%22COR%22%3A+Understanding+the+Role+of+Resources+in+Conservation+of+Resources+Theory&amp;rft.volume=40&amp;rft.issue=5&amp;rft.pages=1334-1364&amp;rft.date=2014&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1177%2F0149206314527130&amp;rft.aulast=Halbesleben&amp;rft.aufirst=J.B.&amp;rft.au=Paustian-Underdal%2C+S.C.&amp;rft.au=Westman%2C+M&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AConservation+of+resources+theory\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Cannon, Walter (1932). <i>The wisdom of the body</i>. New York: W W Norton &amp; Co.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_f